content:
Minimal fix: kill long single-txn full-scan. Add index on `expires_at`, batch delete with small LIMIT + per-batch commit + tiny sleep. No infra change, reaper still runs, pool never held >few ms per batch.

```sql
-- migration: make reaper cheap
CREATE INDEX CONCURRENTLY IF NOT EXISTS idx_sessions_expires_at
  ON sessions (expires_at)
  WHERE expires_at IS NOT NULL;
```

```java
// SessionReaper.java — before: one DELETE, one txn, 4.3s, 1 pool slot held whole time
@Scheduled(fixedDelay = 60_000)           // run every 60s instead of "whenever previous finished + 23min"
public void reap() {
    log.info("starting expired-session reaper");
    int batchSize = 5_000;
    int maxBatchesPerRun = 200;           // cap per run so we can't monopolize
    long start = System.currentTimeMillis();
    int totalDeleted = 0;

    for (int i = 0; i < maxBatchesPerRun; i++) {
        int deleted = txTemplate.execute(status ->
            jdbc.update(
                "DELETE FROM sessions " +
                "WHERE ctid IN (" +
                "  SELECT ctid FROM sessions " +
                "  WHERE expires_at < now() " +
                "  ORDER BY expires_at " +
                "  LIMIT ?" +
                ")",
                batchSize
            )
        );
        totalDeleted += deleted;
        if (deleted < batchSize) break;   // drained
        try { Thread.sleep(50); } catch (InterruptedException e) {
            Thread.currentThread().interrupt(); break;
        }
    }
    log.info("reaped {} sessions in {}ms", totalDeleted, System.currentTimeMillis() - start);
}
```

Why this works: each batch = ~indexed delete of 5k rows, <100ms, own txn → connection returned to pool between batches, no row/gap locks held across seconds, no DB CPU spike. Running every 60s keeps up with growth without ever accumulating 8M scan cost.
